Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
deleteNet(25.10)                                              deleteNet(25.10)

Name
       deleteNet - Logically deletes nets from a design

Syntax
       deleteNet

       [-help]

       <netName>

       [-bus <startId>:<endId>]

       [-moduleBased <verilogModule>]

       Logically deletes nets from a design. If a net is routed, wire segments
       associated with the net are also deleted.

       If  you  plan  to  call ecoRoute -modifyOnlyLayers bottomLayer:topLayer
       later, ensure that the net to be deleted only has wire segments on  the
       specified layer.

       Note: To delete wire segments associated with a net without deleting it
       logically, use the editDelete command.

       You  can  use  wildcards  (*?)  to specify the nets you want Innovus to
       delete.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information for each deleteNet.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man deleteNet

       -bus <startId>:<endId>
              Deletes  the  specified bus bits. The specified bus bit net must
              be a one pin net, which means that the bus bit net  is  floating
              on  the  other side. The specified range must be adjacent to the
              most significant bit or the least significant bit of the  exist-
              ing bus. Also, it must have the same ascending or descending or-
              der as the existing bus.

              Note: PG bus net is not supported.

       -moduleBased <verilogModule>
              Deletes the net from the specified verilog module.

       <netName>
              Specifies the name of the net to delete.

Example
              * The following command deletes one bit h1/net2[3] from existing
                bus h1/net2[3:0]:

                deleteNet h1/net2 -bus 3:3

              * The  following command deletes two bits h1/net2[3], h1/net2[2]
                from existing bus h1/net2[3:0]:

                deleteNet h1/net2 -bus 3:2

              * The following command deletes net1:

                deleteNet net1

              * The following command deletes all nets whose name  begin  with
                net1:

                deleteNet net1*

Related Information
              * addNet

              * ecoRoute

              * editDelete

